What is a Pointer?
A pointer stores the memory address of a value.
ğŸ‘‰ Instead of copying data, we refer to its memory.

x := 10
p := &x   // address of x

& â†’ address operator
* â†’ dereference operator

fmt.Println(*p) // 10

Why Pointers Are Needed?
  âœ” Modify original value
  âœ” Avoid copying large data
  âœ” Improve performance
  âœ” Required for methods & structs

- Pointer Zero Value
  var p *int
  Zero value = nil
  Dereferencing nil â†’ panic

- Pointers with Functions (VERY IMPORTANT)

  func update(x *int) {
      *x = 100
  }
  
  a := 10
  update(&a)
  fmt.Println(a) // 100

ğŸ“Œ Interview Point:
Go passes arguments by value, pointers allow mutation.

-*-*-*-* Pointers with Structs (VERY IMPORTANT)
type User struct {
    Name string
}

func update(u User) {
    u.Name = "Go"
}
âŒ Original struct NOT changed.

*-*- Struct with pointer
  func update(u *User) {
    u.Name = "Go"
}
âœ” Original struct changed.

-*-*-*- Pointer Receiver in Methods (INTERVIEW FAVORITE)
func (u *User) updateName(name string) {
    u.Name = name
}
  âœ” Needed when:
  Modifying struct
  Struct is large

-*- * Pointers with Arrays

arr := [3]int{1, 2, 3}
func modify(a *[3]int) {
    a[0] = 100
}
âœ” Array updated.

*-*-=  Pointers with Slices (TRICKY)
func modify(s []int) {
    s[0] = 99
}
âœ” Works without pointer
ğŸ“Œ Slice header copied, array shared.


When pointer to slice is needed?
func appendSlice(s *[]int) {
    *s = append(*s, 10)
}

-/*/* Pointers with Maps
func update(m map[string]int) {
    m["a"] = 10
}
âœ” No pointer needed
ğŸ“Œ Maps are reference types.


new vs make (POINTER VIEW)
p := new(int)
  Allocates memory
  Returns pointer
  Zero value

- make
s := make([]int, 5)
Initializes slice/map/channel
Returns value (not pointer)

- Pointer to Pointer
  x := 10
  p := &x
  pp := &p
Rarely used, but valid.

*-*-* Pointer Safety Rules
âœ” No pointer arithmetic
âœ” Garbage collected
âœ” Safe memory access

****** A pointer in Go stores the memory address of a value and is used to modify data, reduce copying, and work efficiently with functions and data structures.

- Quick Memory Trick
  & â†’ get address
  * â†’ get value
  Functions get copies
  Pointer = modify original

























